In[]:
# Determine the number of rows containing outliers
percentile25 = df1['time_spend_company'].quantile(0.25)
percentile75 = df1['time_spend_company'].quantile(0.75)

iqr = percentile75 - percentile25

upper_limit = percentile75 + 1.5 * iqr
lower_limit = percentile25 - 1.5 * iqr

outlier = df1[(df1['time_spend_company'] > upper_limit)|(df1['time_spend_company']<lower_limit)]

I want to predict if the employee will leave the company or not.

Since whether employee leaves or not is categorical (0 or 1), we can build a logistic regression model. We can also use a tree based machine learning model.

#since salary has an order (low, medium, high), we need to encode it using cat codes

#there isn't any sort of order for department so we can use get dummies
df_encode = pd.get_dummies(df_encode, drop_first= False)

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.25, stratify = y, random_state = 42)
In[]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
In[]:

                           precision    recall  f1-score   support

Predicted would not leave       0.86      0.93      0.90      2321
    Predicted would leave       0.44      0.26      0.33       471

                 accuracy                           0.82      2792
                macro avg       0.65      0.60      0.61      2792
             weighted avg       0.79      0.82      0.80      2792

The logistic regression model weighted average scores were quite high with a precision score of 79%, a recall score of 82%, and a f1-score of 80%. It also got an accuracy score of 82% but since we are trying to predict who would leave, the respective scores of that is quite low at 44% for precision, 26% for recall, and 33% for f1-score.
